Some of the field trip participants included Jim Moore (and his wife whose name I can't remember), Peter Robertwhaw, Chris Verma, and Pam Quitttmeyer. We started at Salton Sea NWR HQ, walking the trail to Rock Hill, and then spent the rest of the day driving to various locations, including the north end of Garst Road and adjacent Schrimpf Road, the IID wetlands near Niland, Lack Road north of Lindsey Road, Unit 1 SSNWR, and Cattle Call Park and Thornton Park in Brawley. Weather was mostly clear with a few clouds, a light breeze blowing most of the day, relatively high humidity, with temps ranging from 79-102 degrees F.

This list represents all the birds seen while fly fishing and in residence at the Osprey Cabin at Goodrich Creek for three days.  We arrived at 1500 on July 19 and departed at noon on July 22.  The numbers represent the most species seen at one time or in completely different areas on the same day.  Hopefully this correctly indicates the species numbers and diversity at this incredible mountain meadow of nearly 1000 Acres.  The surrounding forest was ponderosa pine and a two needle pine (lodgepole?) at the Osprey and mixed fir/pine at the A Frame.   The elevation is approx 5000'.  It was cloudy and 65 degrees when we arrived, reached 40 or less at night and was sunny and calm and in the low 80's in the daytime for the remainder of our stay.  Great Horned Owl feathers were found but not counted.  I also thought I might have heard E.Gros, Red Crossbills and where was that creeper?
SPECIES COMMENTS: Caught a fine fish as we watched.

TRIP COMMENTS: Time: 0717-0852; clear, calm, 66-74 deg F.  I walked from the north side of the Wildlife Area down the main trail to Burbank Blvd., then under Burbank down the Haskell Ck. trail to the L. A. River Channel; the I retraced my route back to Burbank Blvd. and worked through the coyote brush-dominate fields NE of Burbank and Woodley, then back to the car.  I ran into Irwin Woldman, Chris Verma and Jim Moore in my travels.  I spent some time looking at the two large lerp-infested eucalyptus trees along Haskell Ck. just above the L. A. River channel, where a male Rose-breasted Grosbeak has been present for several darys, but it did not put in an appearance in the limited time I had.  I also missed the Scissor-tailed Flycatcher that had been in the area NE of Burbank and Woodley, even though I was able to follow 5 Western Kingbirds around that area for some time.  One Red Rock Skimmer seen flying over coyote brush field.

TRIP COMMENTS: Boat Trip - Sea & Sage Audubon UNB Monthly Boat Trip/Bird Count.--Date: 3/21/11 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Tide: high at 9:30 am. Skipper: Tom Weiss--Birders who took part in the count: Darrell Wilson, Chris Johnson, Deana Collins, Nancy Kenyon, Bob--Muenckler. Comments: It was very peaceful out on the water. The air was still and we had good reflections--all the way up the channel along with nice views of the snow-clad San Gabriel Mts. in the hazy distance. The--Brown Pelicans and Forster��s Terns were very active, flying up and down the channel and diving for food. We--saw 2 pairs of American White Pelicans, an uncommon sight at Back Bay. An adult female Goldeneye was--seen swimming with a male Bufflehead �� probably the same Goldeneye we spotted last month. Two--Ospreys were sitting on the nesting platform at Shellmaker. The tide was high, resulting in few mudflats. With--the exception of the usual mudflat by the Big Canyon outflow where the Black Skimmers were, our sighting of--shorebird flocks on the land was restricted to low-lying spots on the pickleweed where groups of godwits,--willets, and small sandpipers were packed together tightly. We saw a large Sea Lion sunning himself on a--floating dock, while another was in the water, swimming. A Common Raven was munching on something in--the pickleweed. On a float by the boat rental place, we saw 30 cormorants and 32 pelicans perched in a long--row.

TRIP COMMENTS: Date: 4/18/12 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Tide: outgoing Skipper: Mary Allyson--Birders: Deana Collins, Barbara Demory, Sharon Harrow, Nancy Kenyon, Sally Menzel, Darrell Wilson.--Comments: While we were waiting to get on the boat, we saw a couple of Rock Pigeons fly into openings below the--boat��s deck, surmising they had chosen those spots for nest sites. Sure enough, when we returned to the dock after our--trip was over, we were greeted by frantic parents who wasted no time in flying to their hidden nest sites. We were--surprised to see a Common Loon in basic plumage swimming in the channel by the Sea Base. As we passed the island--below the PCH bridge, we saw a ground squirrel and wondered how he got there since the island is surrounded by fairly--deep water. The 3 Great Blue Herons were busy feeding on stuff in the ice plant and there were a number of plastic water--bottles on the island, supposedly blown there by last week��s wind. On an exposed mud flat below Shellmaker, we saw a--large flock of Elegant & Caspian Terns, Black Skimmers, and Western Sandpipers packed closely together on that small--piece of land. A sea lion with an orange flipper tag was sunning himself on one of the floating docks and in the distance--we saw a Red-tailed Hawk kiting in the wind. Both the Double-crested Cormorants and Brown Pelicans were making good--use of the buoys as perch sites and 13 pelicans were perched in a row on a floating pipe. On the little island above the--salt dike, 25 skimmer decoys had been placed in a row to help encourage the skimmers to nest there. Hopefully, the--decoys looked more realistic to the live skimmers! To us, they looked very unnatural, especially since they were facing in--the wrong direction. Though it was incredibly cold out there, spring was definitely in the air. Most of the avocets were in--alternate plumage as were the Eared Grebes and the pelicans, and a pair of Forster��s Terns were getting a head start on--nesting season by mating. The ducks were paired off, a Western Grebe was calling, and at the nesting platform on--Shellmaker, we saw 3 chicks in the Osprey nest. (We also noticed the absence of nesting material on the platform and--figured it had been blown away by last week��s wind.) It was a great morning with lots of interesting things to see.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Nesting Platform on Shellmaker Island: 2 adults and 3 chicks. Additional adult flying over salt dike near Muth Center.

As we passed the island--below the PCH bridge, we saw a ground squirrel and wondered how he got there since the island is surrounded by fairly--deep water. The 3 Great Blue Herons were busy feeding on stuff in the ice plant and there were a number of plastic water--bottles on the island, supposedly blown there by last week��s wind. On an exposed mud flat below Shellmaker, we saw a--large flock of Elegant & Caspian Terns, Black Skimmers, and Western Sandpipers packed closely together on that small--piece of land. A sea lion with an orange flipper tag was sunning himself on one of the floating docks and in the distance--we saw a Red-tailed Hawk kiting in the wind. Both the Double-crested Cormorants and Brown Pelicans were making good--use of the buoys as perch sites and 13 pelicans were perched in a row on a floating pipe. On the little island above the--salt dike, 25 skimmer decoys had been placed in a row to help encourage the skimmers to nest there. Hopefully, the--decoys looked more realistic to the live skimmers! To us, they looked very unnatural, especially since they were facing in--the wrong direction. Though it was incredibly cold out there, spring was definitely in the air. Most of the avocets were in--alternate plumage as were the Eared Grebes and the pelicans, and a pair of Forster��s Terns were getting a head start on--nesting season by mating. The ducks were paired off, a Western Grebe was calling, and at the nesting platform on--Shellmaker, we saw 3 chicks in the Osprey nest. (We also noticed the absence of nesting material on the platform and--figured it had been blown away by last week��s wind.) It was a great morning with lots of interesting things to see.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Nesting Platform on Shellmaker Island: 2 adults and 3 chicks. Additional adult flying over salt dike near Muth Center.

Date: 6/20/12 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Tide: incoming high tide Skipper: Eric Walker--Birders who helped with the count: Lori Caldwell, Deana Collins, Sharon Harrow, Chris Johnson, Nancy--Kenyon, Garett Lepper, Sally Menzel, Jim Stacy, Margo Stuart, Darrell Wilson.--Comments: The water was very still and we even had a few reflections along the shore on the way up the--channel. The lighting was perfect for birding with none of the usual glare on the water. At 9:15, the sun--partially emerged from the fog. On the way back to the dock, an exceedingly cold breeze sprung up, rippling--the water. Many of the birds were quite active. We saw a number of swallows swooping low over the--pickleweed. On an exposed branch, Barn Swallows were feeding their young. Least & Forster��s Terns were--flying up and down the channel, calling to each other. Two of them flew so close to the boat, we thought they--were going to collide with it. Several of the Black Skimmers were skimming the water, Snowy Egrets were--stalking their prey in the shallow water, and one of the Great Blue Herons was busy eating a small Ray. Two--hummers zipped past our boat . A Red-tailed Hawk was being harassed by a couple of Western Gulls. There--were many more crows around than usual. We got good views of a Western Gull sitting on its nest on the roof--of one of the houses alongside the bay. At the island on the west side in the upper part of the bay, the one that--is ��decorated�� with Black Skimmer decoys, we were surprised to see a tightly-packed flock of 55 Black-bellied--Plovers, some in full breeding plumage, and a few Killdeer. It was a great morning to be out birding!
UCI - Sheila Harlow & Darrell Wilson

Boat Trip - Date: 8/22/12 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Tide: incoming Skipper: Tom Weiss--Birders who actively contributed to the count: Sally Menzel, Darrell Wilson, Deana Collins, Nancy Kenyon.--Comments: The temperature was very pleasant (probably in the mid 70��s) and the sky was cloudy, so the--lighting was perfect for viewing the birds. The tide was slowly coming in which meant we had a few exposed--mudflats as well as areas of very shallow water in which the shorebirds were wading around in water quite a--ways out from the shore. We saw lots of fish ��jumping�� out of the water as well as a giant flock of Western--Sandpipers which erupted from the shore and flew off a giant undulating flock. On a small ice plant clad island--just above the PCH bridge, we saw a huge flock of Black-bellied Plovers crammed together along with a--smaller flock of Western Sandpipers, looking very much like jagged gray rocks until we got closer to them. We--found it next to impossible to count all the plovers because they were packed so tightly together, so Darrell--Wilson photographed them and then made the final count on his computer monitor when he returned home;--he counted a grand total of 248 Black-bellied Plovers roosting on top of that small island! There were very few--raptors flying around so we were happy to see a Red-tailed Hawk perched on the cliff face. The highlight of the--morning was seeing a Clapper Rail which remained in plain view for a couple of minutes, allowing everyone on--board to see it. (Thanks Sally for finding it for us!) We also heard 2 of them vocalizing. A flock of Black--Skimmers flew back and forth alongside our boat, finally landing on a small mudflat which didn��t have enough--room for them all, and it was fun watching the last of the flock trying to find a spot to land. We had a wonderful--morning of birding and look forward to next month!

UNB - Date: 9/19/12 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Tide: High; incoming Skipper: Eric Walker--Birders who took part in the count: Sharon Harrow, Darrell Wilson, Chris Johnson, Chuck Nichols, Deana--Collins, and Nancy Kenyon. Keith Colmar was actively engaged and helped when he could.--Comments: It was a wonderful morning to be out in the bay! The weather was warm and comfortable, not too--hot or too cold. The water was still as glass, providing perfect reflections. Due to the high tide, there were very--few mudflats, so the shorebirds were bunched tightly together on the few available spots of land. We again--saw a large flock of Black-bellied Plovers, Willets, and Western Sandpipers packed tightly together on the--reddish ice plant-clad island near the PCH bridge, looking like small jagged gray rocks from a distance. (We--figured they were waiting for the tide to change.) An American Kestrel was perched on top of a flag pole.--Chris Johnson and Darrell Wilson spotted 2 different Clapper Rails in the Cord Grass and Darrell found the bird--of the day for us �� an American Bittern. It was in the ��Narrows�� area opposite the Dover Cliffs, on the east--side of the channel, only visible from the water. At first the bittern was in the classic bittern pose with beak--pointing upward, but then ��he�� went into his stalking mode, neck outstretched in a slanted position, and we got--great views of his large feet as he slowly moved forward. (As is usually the case with the birds we see from the--boat, he paid no attention to us or our boat.) At a small island-like protuberance along the west shore near--Constellation Dr, we found a tight mass of Marbled Godwits, Willits, Black Skimmers, and a couple of Snowy--Egrets. We saw evidence of recent migratory bird arrivals: 4 Spotted Sandpipers were close together in one--spot, and we saw a total of 44 very active Eared Grebes, some of which were still in groups. All of us agreed--this was one of the best mornings we have ever had in Upper Newport Bay on the pontoon boat! Next month,--we expect to see more ducks, more species of shorebirds, and more raptors.

The water was still as glass, providing perfect reflections. Due to the high tide, there were very--few mudflats, so the shorebirds were bunched tightly together on the few available spots of land. We again--saw a large flock of Black-bellied Plovers, Willets, and Western Sandpipers packed tightly together on the--reddish ice plant-clad island near the PCH bridge, looking like small jagged gray rocks from a distance. (We--figured they were waiting for the tide to change.) An American Kestrel was perched on top of a flag pole.--Chris Johnson and Darrell Wilson spotted 2 different Clapper Rails in the Cord Grass and Darrell found the bird--of the day for us �� an American Bittern. It was in the ��Narrows�� area opposite the Dover Cliffs, on the east--side of the channel, only visible from the water. At first the bittern was in the classic bittern pose with beak--pointing upward, but then ��he�� went into his stalking mode, neck outstretched in a slanted position, and we got--great views of his large feet as he slowly moved forward. (As is usually the case with the birds we see from the--boat, he paid no attention to us or our boat.) At a small island-like protuberance along the west shore near--Constellation Dr, we found a tight mass of Marbled Godwits, Willits, Black Skimmers, and a couple of Snowy--Egrets. We saw evidence of recent migratory bird arrivals: 4 Spotted Sandpipers were close together in one--spot, and we saw a total of 44 very active Eared Grebes, some of which were still in groups. All of us agreed--this was one of the best mornings we have ever had in Upper Newport Bay on the pontoon boat! Next month,--we expect to see more ducks, more species of shorebirds, and more raptors.

Because of the high tide we saw 40 Clapper Rail and 11 Sora perched on logs and the top of the grass or Pickle Weed that they normally hide in. All of the mud flats were submerged so the shorebirds were bunched up in the ice plant on the island near PCH or on the salt dike near the Muth Center. Much of the vegetation has been cleared from the salt dike area so it was easy to see the large flock of Black-bellied Plovers in that area. As I write this I also realized that the Black Skimmer decoys have been removed from that area. We won��t be tempted to count them anymore. There were small numbers of ducks in evidence but only 5 different species.

TRIP COMMENTS: I wanted to spend more time with the Yellow-crowned Night-Heron, but was also interested in a different access route (Doug Willick is still on crutches). I parked at the end of Allstone Drive at the southwest corner of the residential area bordering the inland side of Bolsa Chica. From there it was a 300 feet to the Wintersburg Channel and then another 1,000 feet or so to the pedestrian bridge that crosses over to northeast corner of the Pocket Marsh. I found the YCNH on the far side near where I saw it on Wednesday. The views were distant but identifiable, I guess, but certainly not satisfying. I then took a loop around the whole Pocket Marsh before returning inland along the west dike of the channel. I spotted a Ferruginous Hawk foraging over the agricultural field (Shea Homes property) so continued along the channel past the bridge. I was able to photograph this immature hawk on the ground before it departed off to the east (digiscoped it in flight too!). I returned to my car at about 1030. Some birds:

Date: 12/19/12 Trip Leader: Nancy Kenyon Tide: incoming tide Skipper: Eric Walker--Birders who contributed to the count: Nancy Kenyon, Sally Menzel, Cat & Robert Waters, Chris Johnson, Sharon--Harrow, Carolyn Noble.--Comments: It was low tide when we started out so there was an ample supply of mudflats and exposed shoreline. In--previous months when it was high tide, the island by the PCH bridge was packed solid with shorebirds, but this morning,--there were very few birds on top of the island or on its shores. Further up the channel, we noticed that the sandpipers--were scattered all over the mudflats, looking very much like small white pebbles from a distance. We encountered some--unexpected sightings: 2 Common Loons, one of which appeared to be in breeding plumage; 4 Horned Grebes swimming--together; a group of 14 Surf Scoters near the PCH bridge; a lone Common Goldeneye; a White-tailed Kite perched on--top of a pole near the water, munching on something; a Reddish Egret with the Snowy Egrets; 2 American White--Pelicans; a group of 20 Redheads. It was extremely cold and many of the Willits were hopping around on one leg.

TRIP COMMENTS: After checking the wildlife area for the Gyrfalcon, Howard King and I spent some time looking for a Harlan's Hawk that had been reported along the Ramona Expressway in the vicinity of the dry river channel about a mile west of Davis Road and Lakeview.  During our first visit to this site (10:35-10:55 am), we drove the expressway, along Martin Road, and around several other dirt roads in this area to see if we could locate the hawk either as it perched in the scattered trees or as it flew overhead.  Having not found this bird during our first attempt, we tried again mid-day and eventually saw the hawk as it perched in what appears to be its favorite tree along the dry river channel just south of the expressway.  We tried to approach for better views, but this bird was quite wary, so it flew off when still at moderate range.  During this search, we checked the open fields, the scattered trees, and an old olive orchard that was in the vicinity of what had once been the Lakeview Hot Springs.  We had high clouds, little or no breeze (<5 knots), and temperatures probably in the low to mid-60s.  10:35-10:55 am, and again, 11:50 am - 12:05 pm.

TRIP COMMENTS: Howard King and I began the day at the south end of Johnson Street checking the marsh in the hope of finding a Black Rail in what appears to be some of the best habitat for marsh birds at the north end of the Salton Sea (6:15-6:45 am).  After checking this site, we drove over to the end of Lincoln Street, from which we walked out the east levee road to the mouth of the Whitewater River (7:00 am - 12:00 pm).  The scrub lining the channel for about the first third of this walk had been recently cleared, but the riparian corridor remains intact, and even the scrub was intact for the southern two-thirds or so of the walk.  Upon reaching the end of the road, we scanned the extensive flats, the waters off the river mouth, and those of the bays to both the west and east, but we did not cross the river.  We then worked to the northeast along the shoreline around the north end of the bay roughly to a point off Johnson Street, from which we took a diagonal route back to the levee road and to the vehicle.  Given how many birds were present in early January, the selection today was a bit disappointing, with many grebes, cormorants, and pelicans, but few gulls and very few shorebirds.  Our highlights at the river mouth were a Horned Grebe, male and female Surf Scoters, and an adult Western Gull, so it was not quite worth the moderate effort that we expended.  A calling Clapper Rail in the marsh off Johnson Street was certainly the most unexpected species of the day.  It was mostly clear, with a cover of high, thin clouds that was about 30% at dawn but decreasing to less than 20% later in the day, a mild (5 knot or less) breeze that seemed to switch from the northwest to the northeast and eventually to the southeast, and temperatures that were probably in the upper 40s during our dawn visit to Johnson Street, yet ranging from the low 50s to the mid-80s during our walk out to the delta.  6:15 am - 12:00 pm.----Desert Cottontail - 2 (I briefly saw two rabbits, both of which appeared to be cottontails).

TRIP COMMENTS: Howard King and I walked our usual route around Desert Center today in search of whatever migrants or noteworthy birds we could find.  After a quick check of the lakes upon our arrival, we returned to the southwestern corner of the golf course, around which we walked a clockwise loop that began by working north up the west side of the course and then east along its northern perimeter to the northeastern corner.  We next took a brief detour through the desert wash and checked the trees around the Baptist church before crossing Shasta Drive to check the northern part of the lake, the adjacent yards, and the large eucalyptus tree along the northeastern shore of the lake.  We then doubled back along the northern and northwestern shores of the lake and returned to Shasta Drive, which we worked back to the golf course.  From the most northeastern yard bordering the golf course, we walked west checking the northern edges of the yards bordering the course and then we zigzagged our way south through the neighborhood on the west side of the lake to Lake Tamarisk Drive.  We next walked this road west to the edge of the golf course, from which we worked south to the most southwestern yard on the property, where we spent an extended period of time trying to dig out a few migrants.  We then continued east along the southern edges of the yards to the southern lake, around which we walked a clockwise loop up the west side, across the north end, and then back down the east side and around the yards just east of the lake.  We then worked our way back to the northeast checking the edge of the golf course and the large mesquite tree just east of Fountain Cove, from which we looped around the starting point for the golf course and then back to the southwest across the course to its southern edge, along which we walked west to our vehicle at the corner.  Upon completion of this first loop (7:05-11:35 am), we drove to the parking lot for the clubhouse.  After getting a drink and taking a brief break, we began a second loop that took us around the clubhouse, through the playground, east along the northern edge of the park, and then south across the park to the yards off the north end of Catalina Way.  We next worked our way south along Catalina Way to Lake Tamarisk Drive, and then west to the fire station, from which we looped back east along the southern edges of the yards to the southeastern corner of the neighborhood.  After checking the desert at the east end of Lake Tamarisk Drive, we worked our way north to the park behind the yards along Greenvale Way.  We ended our walk today with a counterclockwise loop around the perimeter of the mobile home park and then back south to our vehicle.  After completing this second loop (11:40 am - 1:25 pm), we took a quick trip out to the sewage ponds (1:30-1:40 pm), where we found only a few birds.  Despite the considerable effort expended, we found only a few of the expected migrants and three or four scarce species:  Red-shouldered Hawk, Wilson's and Red-necked Phalaropes, Blue Grosbeak, and Red Crossbill.  Rather distressing was that we found almost all of the palms and larger eucalyptus trees trimmed to a considerable degree and the large eucalyptus tree at the corner of Kaiser and Oasis Roads had been removed altogether.  I cannot imagine this will be good for migrants, particularly in the near term.  It was mostly cloudy (with a 60% cover) when we arrived, but partly cloudy (with a 20% cover) by the time we left the area, and relatively humid the entire time.  Although it was initially calm, a mild (5+ knot) breeze from the north or northwest came up about 8:30 am, and temperatures seemed to increase from the low 80s to the low 100s.  7:05 am - 1:40 pm.----White-tailed Antelope-Squirrel - 1 (I did not see this one identifiably);--Desert Cottontail - 8.

Tom Horner and I were out above the pit by 7 a.m. on this muggy, 66 F overcast morning.  Cheryl Cobbs and Chris Conard joined us about 7:45 a.m. and Dan Kopp around 8:40 a.m.  About 9:15 a.m. Jim Pompy walked up from the Mayhew Drain area, but only stayed about 40 minutes before heading back.   Since he had seen an Orange-crowned Warbler on the way up, I added it to the list.  Jim had to leave before we went walking and that was put off for a while because Laurie fixed delicious arepas for us around 10 a.m.  Chris and Cheryl had not tried them before and are now converts to the arepa-loving birder group who join me from time to time.----Best species today had to be the 12 Black-necked Stilts seen at Killdeer Island by Chris, Dan and me. Migrants were few today with two Lazuli Buntings, two Wilson's Warblers, Pompy's Orange-crowned Warbler in the anise by the parking lot, a Bullock's Oriole and at least two Black-headed Grosbeaks.----We saw a 3-foot rattlesnake across the trail on the other side of the parking lot.  It was the first one seen by me this year, although I did hear a large one in the berry thickets of the pit a month ago.

Upon arriving in Baker, Johnny Bovee, Robert Bates, Doug Karalun, Howard King, Sandra Remley, and I first stopped at the sewage ponds.  Although we had heard that the White Ibis was missed both the previous day and earlier this morning, we walked both the perimeters of the northern ponds that contained water and the road that divided these two ponds.  The southern ponds were dry and extensively vegetated, so we did not spend long checking these.  We found a reasonable selection of ducks and shorebirds, and even a few land-bird migrants, of which our highlight was an essentially unseen waterthrush that I heard calling along the eastern edge of the property (though I glimpsed it in flight once when it flew overhead).  It was mostly clear but with a few high clouds, calm, and with temperatures increasing from the low 90s to the low 100s.  9:30-10:35 am.

We were one of 12 parties participating in the Cachuma Eagle Count sponsored by Santa Barbara County Parks department.  I worked with Paul Keller and Darwin Richardson.  We covered the interior portion of the bay, north of the boom line, which is seldom covered by birdwatchers at any time of year.  This is perhaps the most prolific breeding and wintering habitat area in inland Santa Barbara County.  We were unable to see clearly at the delta of Santa Cruz Creek due to woody snags somewhat blocking the view.  We saw no birds (except perhaps the Pied-billed Grebes) directly associated with the extensive tule marshes on the W margin of the bay.  Weather was upper 30sF at drop off time, rising perhaps 10F after that. We used 3 binoculars and 2 spotting scopes.
Eagle count, together with Peter Schneekloth

Arrived alone, but many other birders were present during the time I was there: Larry Ballard, Jon Dunn, Curtis Marantz, Pete Ginsburg, Stan Whalens, Jim Zimmer, Wim van Dam, Nick Lethaby, Adam Searcy, and a number of others. All had arrived to chase a juvenile Gray Hawk present since 25 November, when it was found by Eric Culbertson. It was partly cloudy, high 50s F, and calm. I started on Via Real, on the north side of US 101, driving and getting out in a couple of places within 0.4 miles or so to the east of the Santa Claus Lane exit. I then drove around to the other side of the freeway, to Santa Claus Lane, where I parked about 0.3 miles west of the exit overpass. I then walked east to the end of Santa Claus Lane along the railroad tracks, and back along the street, also briefly checking a small part of Padaro Lane. After scanning the area with some other birders near where I parked my car, I drove another 0.2 miles west on Santa Claus Lane to check out the Taj Mahal estate, near Carpinteria Salt Marsh. I then got the call from Larry Ballard that the hawk was near where I had been parked previously. I spent about 15 minutes watching the bird before leaving.

SANTA CLAUS LANE (Carpinteria). I came here this morning to see California's first record of a Gray Hawk. The bird was found on Nov. 25 but not widely reported until the 26th. The majority of my time was spent looking at the hawk and only incidentally did I note a few other birds.  7:05a-8:55a. Fair but storm clouds coming, 59��/63��F. o.o: John Luther, Larry Ballard, Tom Benson and about 10 others.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Viewed from the train tracks adjacent basin two of estuary. I was looking south-west into the basin. Three Osprey stood on the mud flat, maybe 60-70 feet from each other. one was eating a fish, the other two were just standing around. After watching this for a few minutes each bird took off one after the other in different direction. One landed on a stack not far from were it had stood. The one with the fish flew east over basin one, the other flew out towards the estuary mouth and then east along the beach and back into the estuary.

LOCALITY: Monterey Bay pelagic (SCZ Co., 2+ mi offshore)
TRIP COMMENTS: aboard 'Pt Sur Clipper' with Mike Johns, skipper; Mark Merlow, deck; leaders Roger Wolfe, Martjin Verdoes, Dan Singer, Matthew Dodder, Blake Matheson, Rod Norden, and me (D. Roberson); chum Alex Rinkert; with Bill Bousman, Don Glasco, Rick Bern, John Brown, Jeff Poklen, Elinor Gates, and more. A sunny but very windy, cool day. Route from Monterey harbor towards Pt. Pinos, then across Mty Bay to Soquel Cyn and into SCZ waters (for 2.5 hrs; this checklist) over 'the fingers', then NW into swell & wind until we turned and rode the waves back to Monterey (but in sun glare). Winds started at Beaufort 4 but up to Beaufort 6 (=20 knots or so) by afternoon. No whales but two large pods of Long-beaked Common Dolphin (1 in MTY, 1 in SCZ, each pod ~200 beasts), plus some Dall's Porpose, a N. Fur-Seal, several molas. All checklist offshore (>1 nmi) only, except for the "inshore" checklist (separate) that includes harbor area & along Cannery Row.
SPECIES COMMENTS: over the boat about 7 miles offshore, the bird seemed to be flying towards the Mty Pen

SPECIES COMMENTS: watched pair during eclipse; day was hot and nest in full sun, initially male was standing in nest over female providing shade. She was sitting on eggs. She fed while he stayed nearby. She flew off for a few minutes, he stayed at nest. She returned and he stood at edge of nest. Just before eclipse maximum, male flew down the canyon. He did not return. Female stayed on nest. Several times she stood and moved nesting material or eggs around. Pair seemed more troubled by increased human activity than declining light from eclipse.

With Chris and Jeremy for Thanksgiving at Bodega Bay.  Beautiful day with low wind, clear sky and high temp 60 degrees F.  I spent the first 3 hours (high tide) on the north end of the harbor and in the dunes campground.  The late morning was spent at the Tides Wharf observing from the restaurant.  The early afternoon was spent first at Doran Beach, mostly on the harbor side and out onto the mudflat (low tide), and mid-afternoon on Bodega Head (the walk around the south part of the headland).  Then back to Tides Wharf for early Thanksgiving dinner.  As we drove south on CA 1 at 5:20 pm (already dark), a Gray Fox ran across the road in front of us at about the turnoff to Doran Beach (into the willow thicket east of the highway).  Also saw Mule Deer on the headland and Harbor Seal and California Sea Lion in the harbor.  Three whale spouts south of Bodega Head, probably Gray Whales.

LOCALITY: Pt. Mugu Naval Air Station (restricted access)
TRIP COMMENTS: Lead field trip for Conejo Audubon with Martin Ruane and Adam Searcy. Trip ended at 12 and I stayed a few hours later to bird some areas more intensively. We searched a number of areas including the ballfields, airfields, the Perimeter Road to its end at Arnold Road, the adjacent duck clubs, the night-heron roost, the lagoon mouth, estuary, causeway, and nearshore waters. Weather was clear and breezy with wind increasing as the day progressed. Tide was high in the morning when we arrived (5.2 falling), but dropped to expose mudflats by 1100. Sea state was choppy and that in combination with the glare made seawatching difficult.
